Transplant oncology defines any application of transplant medicine and surgery 
aimed at improving cancer patients' survival and/or quality of life. In 
practice, liver transplantation for selected hepato-biliary cancers is the only 
solid organ transplant with demonstrated efficacy in curing cancer. Four are the 
proposed future contributions of transplant oncology in hepato-biliary cancer 
(4-e). (1) evolutionary approach to cancer care that includes liver 
transplantation; (2) elucidation of self and non-self recognition systems, by 
linking tumor and transplant immunology; (3) exploration of innovative endpoints 
both in clinical and experimental settings taking advantage from the access to 
the entire liver explant; (4) extension of surgical limitation in the 
multidisciplinary approach to hepato-biliary oncology. The aim of this review is 
to define the principles of transplant oncology that may be applied to 
hepato-biliary cancer treatment and research, attempting to balance current 
evidences with future opportunities.

